But what is meant by wiſdome from above? 'tis not needful that I uſe many words about it; the ſtrict definition of wiſdome, as diſtinct from prudence, giuen by Philoſophers, and School-men in their Ethical diſcourſes, it don't much concern my Text, nor ſhall I trouble you with it; and for the various acceptations of wiſdome in the Book of God, it might be worth your time to hear them, had I liberty of time to ſpeak them. In this place 'tis evident enough, that we are not to conceive of wiſdome, as diſtinct from prudence, but as including, yea, mainly intending it. I may term it, A Gift of God that inables men to a right judgment, and dictates to them ſuch action as is according to the revealed Will of God: God's revealed Will, or the Scripture, which our Saviour in one of his Quotations calls by the name of Wiſdome. (Luke 11.49. Therefore ſaid the Wiſdome of God, that is the Scripture;) this may be tearmed, ſapientia docens teaching wiſdom; but then there is the gift or grace of wiſdome that rules the judgments, and actions of men, according to the rule of the word, this may be tearmed ſapientia utens, uſing or practiſing wiſdome. Now this wiſdome from
above, 'tis firſt pure, then peaceable;
〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , pure, peaceable; there is the properties of wiſdome in the matter of them: 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 , firſt then; there is the order of them; 'tis pure, 'tis peaceble, 'tis firſt pure, then peaceable.
